To master the scripts you've shared, you should focus on three main documentation hubs: the **pynvme Official Docs**, the **NVMe Specification**, and the **SPDK Reference**.

Since you are running an **Ubuntu system** on a **Dell Latitude**, you are in a great position to use these tools directly. Here are the specific documents and resources you need:

---

## 1. The `pynvme` Documentation (The "How-To")
This is your primary manual. It explains the Python classes (`Controller`, `Namespace`, `Buffer`) used in your examples.

* **Official Web Docs:** [pynvme.readthedocs.io](https://pynvme.readthedocs.io/)
    * *Key Section:* **[Features](https://pynvme.readthedocs.io/en/latest/features.html)** – This explains "Command Callbacks" (Ex 1) and "IOWorkers" (Ex 3 & 5) in plain English.
* **API Reference:** The `api.rst` file in the GitHub repo is the most accurate list of every function available.
    * *Source:* [pynvme/doc/api.rst](https://github.com/pynvme/pynvme/blob/master/doc/api.rst)
* **PyNVMe3 Developer Guide:** If you are using the newer version (PyNVMe3), there is a specialized guide for enterprise features.
    * *Source:* [pynv.me/ssd/dev-guide/](https://pynv.me/ssd/dev-guide/)

## 2. The NVMe Specification (The "Why")
`pynvme` is just a "wrapper" for the NVMe protocol. To understand things like `nvme0.getlogpage(0x02...)` (Ex 5) or `nvme0.id_data(331, 328)` (Ex 2), you need to look at the "Admin Command Set" in the spec.

* **NVM Express Base Specification:** [nvmexpress.org/developers](https://nvmexpress.org/developers/)
    * *What to look for:* Find the **Identify Controller Data Structure** table. It will explain exactly why offset 331 tells you if "Sanitize" is supported.
* **Quick Reference:** Use the [Wikipedia NVM Express page](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NVM_Express) for a faster high-level overview of queues and registers.

## 3. SPDK & Performance Documentation
`pynvme` is built on top of Intel’s **SPDK (Storage Performance Development Kit)**. This is why it’s so fast—it bypasses the Linux kernel entirely.

* **SPDK Getting Started:** [spdk.io/doc/getting_started.html](https://spdk.io/doc/getting_started.html)
    * *Why this matters:* It explains **Hugepages** and **Userspace Drivers**. If your scripts aren't running, it's usually because the SPDK environment isn't "set up" (via `make setup`).
* **SPDK NVMe Driver Doc:** [spdk.io/doc/nvme.html](https://spdk.io/doc/nvme.html)

